256
00:18:01,579 --> 00:18:03,246
(Door opens)

257
00:18:03,330 --> 00:18:06,124
What the Christ is this happy horse shit?

258
00:18:06,208 --> 00:18:08,918
He took the Lord's name in vain.
I'm telling the Warden.

259
00:18:09,003 --> 00:18:10,503
With my baton up your ass!

260
00:18:10,588 --> 00:18:12,255
FAT ASS: Let me out of here!

261
00:18:12,339 --> 00:18:15,717
What is your malfunction,
you fat barrel of monkey spunk?

262
00:18:15,801 --> 00:18:16,968
FAT ASS: Please...

263
00:18:17,052 --> 00:18:19,095
I ain't supposed to be here.

264
00:18:19,179 --> 00:18:20,555
Not me!

265
00:18:20,639 --> 00:18:23,099
I ain't gonna count to three, or even one.

266
00:18:23,183 --> 00:18:25,476
Shut the fuck up, or I'll sing you a lullaby!

267
00:18:25,561 --> 00:18:27,395
(Whispers) Shut up, man. Shut up.

268
00:18:27,479 --> 00:18:28,771
There's been a mistake!

269
00:18:28,856 --> 00:18:32,025
You don't understand.
I'm not supposed to be here!

270
00:18:32,109 --> 00:18:33,192
Open that cell.

271
00:18:33,277 --> 00:18:37,447
MAN: Me neither.
You people run this place like a fucking prison!

272
00:18:44,914 --> 00:18:46,956
HADLEY: Son of a bitch.

273
00:18:47,041 --> 00:18:48,917
(Thuds)

274
00:18:49,001 --> 00:18:51,044
(Whimpering)

275
00:18:51,128 --> 00:18:53,212
PRISONER: Take it easy.

276
00:18:58,552 --> 00:19:00,219
(Yelps)

277
00:19:15,986 --> 00:19:19,364
If I hear so much as a mouse fart in here
the rest of the night,

278
00:19:19,448 --> 00:19:23,117
I swear by God and sonny Jesus,
you will all visit the infirmary.

279
00:19:23,202 --> 00:19:25,286
Every last motherfucker in here.

280
00:19:29,208 --> 00:19:32,877
Call the trustees.
Take that tub of shit down to the infirmary.

281
00:19:47,184 --> 00:19:51,896
RED: His first night in the joint,
Andy Dufresne cost me two packs of cigarettes.

282
00:19:51,981 --> 00:19:54,857
He never made a sound.

283
00:19:57,736 --> 00:19:59,821
(Gate buzzer)

284
00:20:10,374 --> 00:20:13,626
GUARD: Tier 3 North. Clear.

285
00:20:13,711 --> 00:20:15,878
Tier 2 South. Clear.

286
00:20:15,963 --> 00:20:17,839
Tier 3 South. Clear.

287
00:20:17,923 --> 00:20:19,882
Tier 1 North...

288
00:20:19,967 --> 00:20:22,760
- Tier 1 South. Clear.
- Tier 4 South. Clear.

289
00:20:22,845 --> 00:20:24,929
Prepare to roll out.

290
00:20:28,308 --> 00:20:30,393
GUARD: Roll out!

291
00:21:23,280 --> 00:21:26,074
Are... Are you going to eat that?

292
00:21:26,158 --> 00:21:29,077
I hadn't... I hadn't planned on it.

293
00:21:30,329 --> 00:21:31,370
Do you mind?

294
00:21:38,712 --> 00:21:41,339
Ah...that's nice and ripe.

295
00:21:46,095 --> 00:21:48,179
(Chirps)

296
00:21:52,935 --> 00:21:55,394
Jake says thank you.

297
00:21:55,479 --> 00:21:57,897
Fell out of his nest over by the plate shop.

298
00:22:00,150 --> 00:22:04,695
I'm going to look after him
until he's big enough to fly.

299
00:22:04,780 --> 00:22:06,572
Oh, no, no. Here he comes.

300
00:22:09,701 --> 00:22:13,621
Morning, fellas. Fine morning, ain't it?

301
00:22:13,705 --> 00:22:16,124
You know why it's a fine morning, don't you?

302
00:22:16,208 --> 00:22:18,626
Come on. Set 'em down.
I want 'em all lined up here,

303
00:22:18,710 --> 00:22:21,504
just like a pretty little chorus line.

304
00:22:21,588 --> 00:22:23,673
Yeah, look at that!

305
00:22:23,757 --> 00:22:26,634
- Look at that. Oh, Lord!
- I can't stand this guy.

306
00:22:26,718 --> 00:22:27,760
(Inhales)

307
00:22:27,845 --> 00:22:30,513
Yes. Richmond, Virginia.

308
00:22:30,597 --> 00:22:32,682
- Smell my ass!
- After he smells mine.

309
00:22:32,766 --> 00:22:38,104
Gee, Red, it was a terrible shame
about your horse coming in last, an' all.

310
00:22:38,188 --> 00:22:41,399
But I sure do love that winning horse of mine,
though.

311
00:22:41,483 --> 00:22:44,193
I owe that boy a great big, sloppy kiss
when I see him.

312
00:22:44,278 --> 00:22:47,280
Why don't you give him some of your cigarettes,
instead?

313
00:22:47,364 --> 00:22:49,157
Lucky fuck.

314
00:22:49,241 --> 00:22:50,950
Hey, Tyrell.

315
00:22:51,034 --> 00:22:53,995
You pull infirmary duty this week?

316
00:22:54,079 --> 00:22:55,788
How's that horse of mine doing?

317
00:22:55,873 --> 00:22:57,331
Dead.

318
00:22:57,416 --> 00:23:02,795
Hadley busted his head up pretty good.
The doc had already gone home for the night.

319
00:23:02,796 --> 00:23:05,548
Poor bastard lay there till this morning.

320
00:23:05,632 --> 00:23:08,467
By then, hell, there weren't nothing we could do.

321
00:23:14,266 --> 00:23:15,850
What was his name?

322
00:23:19,104 --> 00:23:20,479
What did you say?

323
00:23:22,357 --> 00:23:24,734
I was just wondering if anyone knew his name.

324
00:23:24,818 --> 00:23:27,528
What the fuck do you care, new fish?

325
00:23:28,989 --> 00:23:32,366
It doesn't fuckin' matter what his name was.
He's dead.

326
00:23:51,720 --> 00:23:54,055
Hey...

327
00:23:54,139 --> 00:23:56,891
Anybody come at you yet?

328
00:23:58,393 --> 00:24:00,394
Anybody get to you yet?

329
00:24:01,521 --> 00:24:04,565
Hey, we all need friends in here.

330
00:24:04,650 --> 00:24:06,567
I could be a friend to you.

331
00:24:09,029 --> 00:24:10,696
Hey...

332
00:24:15,535 --> 00:24:17,411
Hard to get.

333
00:24:19,081 --> 00:24:20,748
I like that.

334
00:24:27,381 --> 00:24:30,675
RED: Andy kept pretty much to himself at first.

335
00:24:30,759 --> 00:24:33,219
I guess he had a lot on his mind,

336
00:24:33,303 --> 00:24:35,513
trying to adapt to life on the inside.

337
00:24:37,057 --> 00:24:39,767
It wasn't until a month went by
that he opened his mouth

338
00:24:39,851 --> 00:24:42,144
to say more than two words to somebody.

339
00:24:44,064 --> 00:24:46,107
As it turned out...

340
00:24:46,191 --> 00:24:48,109
that somebody was me.

341
00:24:51,697 --> 00:24:55,866
TANNOY: Officers Russell and Burwell
report to the duty officer.

342
00:24:56,910 --> 00:24:59,662
I'm Andy Dufresne.

343
00:24:59,746 --> 00:25:01,831
The wife-killing banker.

344
00:25:03,667 --> 00:25:05,376
Why did you do it?

345
00:25:05,460 --> 00:25:07,086
I didn't, since you ask.

346
00:25:07,170 --> 00:25:10,214
(Laughs) You're gonna fit right in!

347
00:25:10,299 --> 00:25:13,467
Everybody in here's innocent.
Didn't you know that?

348
00:25:13,552 --> 00:25:16,887
- Heywood, what are you in here for?
- Didn't do it. Lawyer fucked me.

349
00:25:19,808 --> 00:25:22,601
Rumor has it you're a real cold fish.

350
00:25:22,686 --> 00:25:26,439
You think your shit smells sweeter than most.
Is that right?

351
00:25:26,523 --> 00:25:28,858
- What do you think?
- To tell you the truth,

352
00:25:28,942 --> 00:25:32,028
I haven't made up my mind. (Chuckles)

353
00:25:32,112 --> 00:25:36,198
I understand
you're a man that knows how to get things.

354
00:25:36,283 --> 00:25:39,785
I'm known to locate certain things,
from time to time.

355
00:25:39,870 --> 00:25:42,872
- I wonder if you might get me a rock hammer.
- A what?

356
00:25:42,956 --> 00:25:44,332
A rock hammer.

357
00:25:44,416 --> 00:25:46,709
- What is it, and why?
- What do you care?

358
00:25:48,587 --> 00:25:51,464
Well, if it was a toothbrush, I'd just quote a price,

359
00:25:51,548 --> 00:25:54,133
but then a toothbrush is a non-lethal object.

360
00:25:55,552 --> 00:25:57,261
Fair enough.

361
00:25:57,346 --> 00:25:59,805
A rock hammer
is about six or seven inches long.

362
00:25:59,890 --> 00:26:01,515
Looks like a miniature pickaxe.

363
00:26:01,600 --> 00:26:02,725
Pickaxe?

364
00:26:02,809 --> 00:26:04,894
- For rocks.
- Rocks.

365
00:26:06,563 --> 00:26:08,731
Quartz?

366
00:26:08,815 --> 00:26:10,483
Quartz.

367
00:26:11,735 --> 00:26:14,111
And some mica.

368
00:26:14,196 --> 00:26:15,363
Shale.

369
00:26:16,448 --> 00:26:18,032
Limestone.

370
00:26:18,116 --> 00:26:20,034
So?

371
00:26:20,118 --> 00:26:22,203
So, I'm a rock hound.

372
00:26:22,287 --> 00:26:25,498
At least, I was in my old life.
I'd like to be again on a limited basis.

373
00:26:25,582 --> 00:26:27,708
Or maybe you want
to hammer somebody's skull.

374
00:26:27,793 --> 00:26:29,251
No, sir.

375
00:26:30,379 --> 00:26:31,962
I have no enemies here.

376
00:26:32,047 --> 00:26:34,423
No? Wait a while.

377
00:26:35,967 --> 00:26:38,135
Word gets around.

378
00:26:38,220 --> 00:26:41,347
The Sisters have taken quite a liking to you.

379
00:26:41,431 --> 00:26:43,224
Especially Bogs.

380
00:26:44,309 --> 00:26:48,521
I don't suppose it would help any
if I explained to them I'm not homosexual.

381
00:26:48,605 --> 00:26:50,106
RED: Neither are they.

382
00:26:50,190 --> 00:26:52,900
You have to be human first. They don't qualify.

383
00:26:58,156 --> 00:27:02,701
Bull queers take by force.
It's all they want or understand.

384
00:27:02,786 --> 00:27:06,414
If I were you,
I'd grow eyes in the back of my head.

385
00:27:06,498 --> 00:27:07,832
Thanks for the advice.

386
00:27:07,916 --> 00:27:09,500
Well, that's free.

387
00:27:09,584 --> 00:27:11,836
You understand my concern.

388
00:27:11,920 --> 00:27:14,463
Well, if there's any trouble,
I won't use the hammer.

389
00:27:14,548 --> 00:27:18,759
Then I guess you want to escape.
Tunnel under the wall, maybe.

390
00:27:20,220 --> 00:27:22,012
Did I miss something? What's funny?

391
00:27:22,097 --> 00:27:25,141
You'll understand
when you see the rock hammer.

392
00:27:27,018 --> 00:27:29,019
What's an item like this usually go for?

393
00:27:29,104 --> 00:27:32,148
Seven dollars in any rock and gem shop.

394
00:27:32,232 --> 00:27:34,942
My normal mark-up's 20 per cent.

395
00:27:34,943 --> 00:27:37,486
But this is a specialty item.

396
00:27:37,571 --> 00:27:40,156
The risk goes up, the price goes up.

397
00:27:40,157 --> 00:27:42,116
Let's make it an even ten bucks.

398
00:27:42,200 --> 00:27:44,076
Ten it is.

399
00:27:45,162 --> 00:27:47,580
Waste of money, if you ask me.

400
00:27:47,664 --> 00:27:49,206
Why's that?

401
00:27:50,292 --> 00:27:53,335
Folks around this joint love surprise inspections.

402
00:27:54,921 --> 00:27:57,214
If they find it, you're gonna lose it.

403
00:27:57,299 --> 00:27:59,425
If they do catch you with it, you don't know me.

404
00:27:59,509 --> 00:28:01,719
Mention my name, we never do business again.

405
00:28:01,803 --> 00:28:04,930
Not for shoelaces or a stick of gum.
Now, you got that?

406
00:28:06,433 --> 00:28:07,850
I understand.

407
00:28:07,934 --> 00:28:09,351
Thank you...

408
00:28:09,352 --> 00:28:10,978
Mr. er...?

409
00:28:11,062 --> 00:28:13,522
Red. The name's Red.

410
00:28:13,523 --> 00:28:14,565
Red?

411
00:28:14,649 --> 00:28:17,401
Why do they call you that?

412
00:28:21,072 --> 00:28:23,157
Maybe it's because I'm Irish.

413
00:28:31,124 --> 00:28:34,168
RED: I could see
why some of the boys took him for snobby.

414
00:28:34,252 --> 00:28:37,671
He had a quiet way about him.

415
00:28:37,756 --> 00:28:42,218
A walk and a talk
that just wasn't normal around here.

416
00:28:42,302 --> 00:28:43,844
He strolled...

417
00:28:43,929 --> 00:28:48,265
like a man in a park,
without a care or worry in the world.

418
00:28:48,350 --> 00:28:53,062
Like he had on an invisible coat
that would shield him from this place.

419
00:28:53,146 --> 00:28:57,316
Yeah. I think it would be fair to say...

420
00:28:57,317 --> 00:28:59,401
I liked Andy from the start.

421
00:29:01,154 --> 00:29:04,365
Let's go!
Some of us have got a schedule to keep.

422
00:29:07,661 --> 00:29:09,745
Move it! Come on. Move it!

423
00:29:13,375 --> 00:29:16,502
Bob, how are you doing?
How's the wife treating you?

424
00:29:26,221 --> 00:29:27,680
Easy.

425
00:29:27,764 --> 00:29:29,848
Keep it moving.

426
00:29:32,644 --> 00:29:33,894
Red...

427
00:29:54,416 --> 00:29:58,627
RED: Andy was right. I finally got the joke.

428
00:29:58,712 --> 00:30:03,215
It would take a man about 600 years
to tunnel under the wall with one of these.

429
00:30:07,554 --> 00:30:08,679
Book?

430
00:30:08,763 --> 00:30:10,639
Not today.

431
00:30:15,979 --> 00:30:18,063
- Book?
- No.

432
00:30:19,858 --> 00:30:21,066
Hey, Brooksy.

433
00:30:24,362 --> 00:30:26,447
Delivery for Dufresne.

434
00:30:33,538 --> 00:30:39,168
Book?

435
00:30:42,172 --> 00:30:44,298
Dufresne...

436
00:30:44,382 --> 00:30:46,550
Here's your book.

437
00:30:50,972 --> 00:30:52,640
Thanks.

438
00:30:56,478 --> 00:30:59,688
Dufresne! We're running low on Hexlite.

439
00:30:59,773 --> 00:31:01,857
Get on back and fetch us up some.

440
00:31:39,062 --> 00:31:41,021
If you get this in your eyes, it blinds you.

441
00:31:41,106 --> 00:31:43,857
Honey...hush.

442
00:31:50,949 --> 00:31:52,825
(Groans)

443
00:31:55,912 --> 00:31:58,330
That's it. You fight.

444
00:31:58,415 --> 00:31:59,998
It's better that way.

445
00:32:00,083 --> 00:32:01,875
(Screaming and yelling)

446
00:32:08,425 --> 00:32:11,260
RED: I wish I could tell you
that Andy fought the good fight,

447
00:32:11,344 --> 00:32:13,887
and the Sisters let him be.

448
00:32:13,972 --> 00:32:15,973
I wish I could tell you that.

449
00:32:16,057 --> 00:32:18,142
But prison is no fairy-tale world.

450
00:32:20,103 --> 00:32:22,229
He never said who did it.

451
00:32:22,313 --> 00:32:25,357
But we all knew.

452
00:32:25,442 --> 00:32:27,317
(Gate buzzer)

453
00:32:28,695 --> 00:32:31,572
Things went on like that for a while.

454
00:32:31,656 --> 00:32:34,283
Prison life consists of routine...

455
00:32:34,367 --> 00:32:36,577
and then more routine.

456
00:32:38,955 --> 00:32:42,791
Every so often,
Andy would show up with fresh bruises.

457
00:32:43,960 --> 00:32:46,003
The Sisters kept at him.

458
00:32:46,087 --> 00:32:50,215
Sometimes he was able to fight 'em off.
Sometimes not.

459
00:32:50,300 --> 00:32:53,552
And that's how it went for Andy.

460
00:32:53,636 --> 00:32:56,180
That was his routine.

461
00:32:56,264 --> 00:33:00,058
I do believe
those first two years were the worst for him.

462
00:33:00,143 --> 00:33:02,394
And I also believe,

463
00:33:02,479 --> 00:33:07,024
if things had gone on that way,
this place would have got the best of him.

464
00:33:07,108 --> 00:33:10,068
But then, in the spring of 1949,

465
00:33:10,153 --> 00:33:12,154
the powers that be decided that...

466
00:33:12,238 --> 00:33:15,657
The roof of the license-plate factory
needs resurfacing.

467
00:33:15,742 --> 00:33:18,494
I need a dozen volunteers for a week's work.

468
00:33:19,662 --> 00:33:21,789
As you know,

469
00:33:21,873 --> 00:33:25,584
special detail carries with it special privileges.

470
00:33:25,668 --> 00:33:27,753
RED: It was outdoor detail...

471
00:33:29,255 --> 00:33:32,841
..and May is one damn fine month
to be working outdoors.

472
00:33:32,926 --> 00:33:34,551
Stay in line there.

473
00:33:34,636 --> 00:33:37,554
More than a hundred men
volunteered for the job.

474
00:33:39,057 --> 00:33:40,724
(Whispers)

475
00:33:41,935 --> 00:33:44,228
Wallace E Unger.

476
00:33:45,396 --> 00:33:47,856
Ellis Redding.

477
00:33:47,941 --> 00:33:50,776
Wouldn't you know it?

478
00:33:50,860 --> 00:33:53,445
Me and some fellows I know
were among the names.

479
00:33:53,530 --> 00:33:55,614
GUARD: Andrew Dufresne.

480
00:33:55,698 --> 00:33:59,243
RED: It only cost us a pack of smokes per man.

481
00:33:59,327 --> 00:34:02,037
I made my usual 20 per cent, of course.

482
00:34:02,121 --> 00:34:05,707
HADLEY: So, this big-shot lawyer
calls me long-distance from Texas.

483
00:34:05,792 --> 00:34:07,501
I say, "Yeah?"

484
00:34:07,585 --> 00:34:11,296
He says, "Sorry to inform you,
but your brother just died."

485
00:34:11,381 --> 00:34:13,882
Oh, damn, Byron. I'm sorry to hear that.

486
00:34:13,967 --> 00:34:15,342
I'm not. He was an asshole.

487
00:34:15,426 --> 00:34:17,761
Ran off years ago.
Figured him for dead, anyway.

488
00:34:17,846 --> 00:34:21,807
So, anyway, this lawyer fella says to me,
"Your brother died a rich man."

489
00:34:21,891 --> 00:34:24,601
Oil wells and shit. Close to a million bucks.

490
00:34:24,686 --> 00:34:27,145
GUARD: A million bucks?

491
00:34:27,230 --> 00:34:29,606
Fucking incredible
how lucky some assholes get.

492
00:34:29,691 --> 00:34:32,234
Jeez-Louise! Are you gonna see any of that?

493
00:34:32,318 --> 00:34:35,404
35,000. That's what he left me.

494
00:34:35,488 --> 00:34:37,406
- Dollars?
- Yeah.

495
00:34:37,490 --> 00:34:40,617
Holy shit! That's great.
That's like winning the sweepstakes.

496
00:34:40,702 --> 00:34:41,910
Isn’t it?

497
00:34:41,995 --> 00:34:45,038
Dumb shit. What do you think
the government's gonna do to me?

498
00:34:45,123 --> 00:34:47,666
Take a big, wet bite out of my ass, is what.

499
00:34:47,667 --> 00:34:51,837
Poor Byron! Terrible fucking luck, huh?

500
00:34:51,921 --> 00:34:54,590
RED: Crying shame.

501
00:34:54,674 --> 00:34:56,341
Some people really got it awful!

502
00:34:56,426 --> 00:34:57,968
Andy, are you nuts?

503
00:34:58,052 --> 00:35:00,178
Keep your eyes on your mop, man. Andy!

504
00:35:00,179 --> 00:35:03,223
GUARD: Well, you'll pay some tax,
but you'll still end up...

505
00:35:03,308 --> 00:35:06,143
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Maybe enough to buy a new car. Then what?

506
00:35:06,227 --> 00:35:08,604
I've got to pay tax on the car.

507
00:35:08,688 --> 00:35:12,566
Repair, maintenance, goddamn kids
pestering me to take them for a ride...

508
00:35:12,650 --> 00:35:16,570
And at the end of the year, you figure the tax
wrong, you pay them out of your own pocket.

