764
00:52:45,827 --> 00:52:48,996
I enter the names on this clipboard here.

765
00:52:49,081 --> 00:52:52,541
Easy-peasy, Japanesey. Any questions?

766
00:52:52,626 --> 00:52:55,586
Brooks, how long have you been librarian?

767
00:52:55,671 --> 00:53:00,841
Oh...I come here in '05,
and they made me librarian in 1912.

768
00:53:00,926 --> 00:53:04,303
And in all that time,
have you ever had an assistant?

769
00:53:04,388 --> 00:53:06,973
No. No, not much to it, really.

770
00:53:07,057 --> 00:53:08,975
Well, why me? Why now?

771
00:53:09,059 --> 00:53:10,559
I don't know,

772
00:53:10,644 --> 00:53:13,980
but it'll be nice to have some company
down here for a change.

773
00:53:13,981 --> 00:53:16,065
HADLEY: Dufresne!

774
00:53:25,367 --> 00:53:27,451
That's him. That's the one.

775
00:53:35,002 --> 00:53:36,293
I'm Dekins.

776
00:53:36,378 --> 00:53:38,838
(Nervously) I was er...

777
00:53:38,922 --> 00:53:42,925
thinking about maybe setting up
some kind of trust fund for my kids' educations.

778
00:53:45,262 --> 00:53:46,721
Oh...

779
00:53:46,805 --> 00:53:48,472
I see.

780
00:53:49,933 --> 00:53:51,809
Well, erm...

781
00:53:53,186 --> 00:53:54,729
..why don't we have a seat,

782
00:53:54,813 --> 00:53:56,897
and talk it over?

783
00:53:59,443 --> 00:54:02,361
Brooks,
do you have a piece of paper and a pencil?

784
00:54:13,832 --> 00:54:15,541
Thanks.

785
00:54:15,625 --> 00:54:17,293
So...

786
00:54:18,545 --> 00:54:21,047
Mr. Dekins...

787
00:54:21,131 --> 00:54:25,593
And then Andy says to Mr. Dekins,
"Do you want your sons to go to Harvard,

788
00:54:25,677 --> 00:54:27,803
- or Yale?"
- He didn't say that?

789
00:54:27,888 --> 00:54:30,556
As God is my witness, he did!

790
00:54:30,640 --> 00:54:34,018
Dekins just blinked for a second.
Then he laughed himself silly.

791
00:54:34,102 --> 00:54:35,978
And afterwards he shook Andy's hand.

792
00:54:36,063 --> 00:54:37,438
My ass!

793
00:54:37,522 --> 00:54:38,731
Shook his hand.

794
00:54:38,815 --> 00:54:41,776
Hell, I...I near soiled myself! (Laughs)

795
00:54:41,860 --> 00:54:46,072
All Andy needed was a suit and a tie
and a little jiggly hula girl on his desk,

796
00:54:46,156 --> 00:54:47,490
and he would have been:

797
00:54:47,574 --> 00:54:49,116
"Mr. Dufresne, if you please"!

798
00:54:49,201 --> 00:54:50,951
Making a few friends, Andy?

799
00:54:51,995 --> 00:54:53,954
I wouldn't say "friends".

800
00:54:54,039 --> 00:54:58,042
I'm a convicted murderer
who provides sound financial planning.

801
00:54:58,126 --> 00:55:00,461
It's a wonderful pet to have.

802
00:55:00,545 --> 00:55:02,463
Got you out of the laundry, though.

803
00:55:02,547 --> 00:55:04,757
Well, it might do more than that.

804
00:55:04,841 --> 00:55:07,843
How about expanding the library?
Get some new books in there.

805
00:55:07,928 --> 00:55:10,638
If you're gonna ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

806
00:55:10,722 --> 00:55:13,182
- Right.
- How do you expect to do that?

807
00:55:13,266 --> 00:55:18,521
I mean, get new books in here,
Mr. Dufresne, if you please?

808
00:55:18,605 --> 00:55:20,356
Ask the Warden for funds.

809
00:55:20,440 --> 00:55:21,690
(Laughter)

810
00:55:21,775 --> 00:55:25,069
Son, son. Six wardens
have been through here in my tenure,

811
00:55:25,153 --> 00:55:28,781
and I've learned one immutable, universal truth.

812
00:55:28,865 --> 00:55:30,574
Not one of them born...

813
00:55:30,575 --> 00:55:35,538
whose asshole wouldn't pucker up tighter than
a snare drum when you asked them for funds.

814
00:55:35,622 --> 00:55:37,915
The budget's stretched thin, as it is.

815
00:55:37,999 --> 00:55:39,250
I see.

816
00:55:39,334 --> 00:55:42,878
Perhaps I could write to the State Senate
and request funds from them.

817
00:55:42,963 --> 00:55:47,341
As far as they're concerned, there's only three
ways to spend money when it comes to prisons:

818
00:55:47,425 --> 00:55:49,510
more walls, more bars and more guards.

819
00:55:49,594 --> 00:55:54,014
Still, I'd like to try, with your permission.
A letter a week. They can't ignore me forever.

820
00:55:54,099 --> 00:55:55,641
Sure can.

821
00:55:55,725 --> 00:55:58,602
But you write your letters, if it makes you happy.

822
00:55:58,687 --> 00:56:00,980
I'll even mail them for you. How's that?

823
00:56:02,899 --> 00:56:05,943
RED: So, Andy started writing a letter a week,

824
00:56:06,027 --> 00:56:08,112
just like he said.

825
00:56:12,159 --> 00:56:16,287
And, just like Norton said, Andy got no answers.

826
00:56:24,129 --> 00:56:29,633
The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.

827
00:56:29,718 --> 00:56:32,803
The year after that, he did them all...

828
00:56:32,888 --> 00:56:34,972
including the Warden's.

829
00:56:36,349 --> 00:56:40,102
The year after that, they rescheduled
the start of the intramural season

830
00:56:40,187 --> 00:56:42,271
to coincide with tax season.

831
00:56:44,566 --> 00:56:48,777
The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.

832
00:56:48,862 --> 00:56:52,990
So, Moresby Prison issued you your gun,
but you had to pay for it?

833
00:56:53,074 --> 00:56:54,825
Damn right. The holster, too.

834
00:56:54,910 --> 00:56:56,160
That's tax-deductible.

835
00:56:56,244 --> 00:56:57,411
You can write that off.

836
00:56:57,495 --> 00:57:00,831
RED: Yes, sir.
Andy was a regular cottage industry.

837
00:57:00,916 --> 00:57:03,959
In fact, it got so busy at tax time...

838
00:57:04,044 --> 00:57:06,086
he was allowed a staff.

839
00:57:06,171 --> 00:57:08,631
Hey, Red, can you hand me a stack of 1040s?

840
00:57:08,715 --> 00:57:11,383
It got me out of the wood shop
a month out of the year,

841
00:57:11,468 --> 00:57:14,136
and that was fine by me.

842
00:57:14,221 --> 00:57:17,598
And still...he kept sending those letters.

843
00:57:22,896 --> 00:57:24,730
Red, Andy.

844
00:57:24,814 --> 00:57:26,023
It's Brooks.

845
00:57:26,107 --> 00:57:28,567
(Men shouting)
- Watch the door.

846
00:57:28,652 --> 00:57:30,236
Please, Brooks.

847
00:57:30,320 --> 00:57:32,321
- Just calm the fuck down.
- Stay back!

848
00:57:32,405 --> 00:57:34,448
- Stay back!
- What the hell's going on?

849
00:57:34,532 --> 00:57:37,618
You tell me. One second he's fine.
Then out comes the knife.

850
00:57:37,702 --> 00:57:40,162
Brooks, we can talk about this. Right?

851
00:57:40,247 --> 00:57:42,373
Nothing to talk about, goddamn it!

852
00:57:42,457 --> 00:57:44,166
I'm gonna cut his fucking throat.

853
00:57:44,251 --> 00:57:46,126
Heywood? Wait, what's he done to you?

854
00:57:46,211 --> 00:57:48,337
It's what they done!

855
00:57:48,421 --> 00:57:49,838
I...I got no choice...

856
00:57:49,923 --> 00:57:52,591
You're not gonna hurt him.
Even Heywood knows that.

857
00:57:52,676 --> 00:57:55,302
- Right, Heywood?
- I...I know that, sure.

858
00:57:55,387 --> 00:57:58,806
You won't hurt him, because he's a friend,
and you're a reasonable man.

859
00:57:58,890 --> 00:58:00,182
That's right. Right, guys?

860
00:58:00,267 --> 00:58:03,644
- Yes.
- So, put the knife down. Brooks, look at me.

861
00:58:03,728 --> 00:58:05,562
Put the knife down.

862
00:58:06,648 --> 00:58:07,815
Brooks...

863
00:58:07,899 --> 00:58:10,150
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

864
00:58:10,235 --> 00:58:12,569
Brooks, look at his neck. It's bleeding.

865
00:58:12,654 --> 00:58:13,821
(Heywood gasps)

866
00:58:13,905 --> 00:58:15,489
It's the only...

867
00:58:15,573 --> 00:58:17,866
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

868
00:58:17,951 --> 00:58:20,536
Come on. This is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

869
00:58:20,537 --> 00:58:22,621
Put it down.

870
00:58:23,957 --> 00:58:26,333
(Brooks sobs)

871
00:58:30,005 --> 00:58:34,717
Come on. Take it easy.
You're going to be all right.

872
00:58:34,801 --> 00:58:36,176
HEYWOOD: Him?

873
00:58:36,261 --> 00:58:39,930
Hell, what about me?
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat.

874
00:58:40,015 --> 00:58:42,641
RED: Shit, Heywood,
you've had worse from shaving.

875
00:58:42,726 --> 00:58:44,977
What the hell did you do to set him off, anyway?

876
00:58:45,061 --> 00:58:47,396
Nothing. I come in here to say fare-thee-well.

877
00:58:47,480 --> 00:58:50,607
Ain't you heard? His parole's come through.

878
00:58:52,652 --> 00:58:55,779
I just don't understand what happened in there.
That's all.

879
00:58:55,864 --> 00:58:58,449
The old man's as crazy
as a rat in a tin shithouse.

880
00:58:58,533 --> 00:59:00,743
Oh, Heywood, that's enough out of you.

881
00:59:00,827 --> 00:59:03,829
- I heard he had you shitting in your pants.
- Fuck you!

882
00:59:03,913 --> 00:59:05,289
Would you knock it off?

883
00:59:05,373 --> 00:59:07,708
Brooks ain't no bug.

884
00:59:07,792 --> 00:59:09,668
He's just...

885
00:59:11,546 --> 00:59:13,380
He's just institutionalized.

886
00:59:14,716 --> 00:59:16,383
Institutionalized, my ass.

887
00:59:16,468 --> 00:59:20,763
The man's been in here 50 years, Heywood.
50 years.

888
00:59:20,847 --> 00:59:22,556
This is all he knows.

889
00:59:22,640 --> 00:59:25,059
In here, he's an important man.

890
00:59:25,143 --> 00:59:26,602
He's an educated man.

891
00:59:26,686 --> 00:59:28,771
Outside, he's nothing.

892
00:59:30,940 --> 00:59:33,567
Just a used-up con with arthritis in both hands.

893
00:59:33,651 --> 00:59:36,862
Probably couldn't get a library card if he tried.

894
00:59:36,946 --> 00:59:39,031
You know what I'm trying to say?

895
00:59:39,115 --> 00:59:41,867
Red, I do believe you're talking out of your ass.

896
00:59:43,119 --> 00:59:46,038
You believe whatever you want, Floyd.

897
00:59:46,039 --> 00:59:48,582
But I'm telling you, these walls are funny.

898
00:59:50,001 --> 00:59:52,086
First you hate 'em...

899
00:59:53,630 --> 00:59:55,714
..then you get used to 'em.

900
00:59:57,342 --> 00:59:59,968
Enough time passes...

901
01:00:00,053 --> 01:00:03,013
you get so you depend on 'em.

902
01:00:03,098 --> 01:00:05,432
That's institutionalized.

903
01:00:05,517 --> 01:00:06,892
JIGGER: Shit.

904
01:00:06,893 --> 01:00:08,519
You can never get like that.

905
01:00:08,603 --> 01:00:10,521
Oh, yeah?

906
01:00:10,605 --> 01:00:13,190
Say that when you've been here
as long as Brooks has.

907
01:00:13,274 --> 01:00:15,150
Goddamn right.

908
01:00:17,487 --> 01:00:20,030
They send you here for life.

909
01:00:20,115 --> 01:00:22,199
That's exactly what they take.

910
01:00:24,119 --> 01:00:26,203
The part that counts, anyway.

911
01:00:29,249 --> 01:00:32,584
(Jake screeches)

912
01:00:33,711 --> 01:00:35,879
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

913
01:00:37,799 --> 01:00:39,633
You go on, now.

914
01:00:40,718 --> 01:00:45,389
You're free.

915
01:01:01,281 --> 01:01:03,157
Bye.

916
01:01:04,242 --> 01:01:06,160
Good luck, Brooks.

917
01:01:42,739 --> 01:01:45,449
BROOKS: Dear fellas...

918
01:01:45,533 --> 01:01:49,745
I can't believe
how fast things move on the outside.

919
01:01:49,829 --> 01:01:51,079
(Horn blares)

920
01:01:51,164 --> 01:01:54,208
Watch it, old-timer! Are you trying to get killed?

921
01:01:54,292 --> 01:01:57,628
I saw an automobile once, when I was a kid,

922
01:01:57,712 --> 01:02:00,631
but now...they're everywhere.

923
01:02:04,844 --> 01:02:08,430
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

924
01:02:24,781 --> 01:02:31,078
The parole board got me into
this halfway house called The Brewer,

925
01:02:31,162 --> 01:02:34,957
and a job bagging groceries at the Foodway.

926
01:02:37,001 --> 01:02:42,339
It's hard work, and I try to keep up,
but my hands hurt most of the time.

927
01:02:42,423 --> 01:02:44,424
WOMAN: Make sure your man double-bags.

928
01:02:44,509 --> 01:02:46,760
Last time, the bottom near came out.

929
01:02:46,844 --> 01:02:50,138
Make sure you double-bag, like the lady says.
Understand?

930
01:02:50,223 --> 01:02:51,682
Yes, sir. I surely will.

931
01:02:51,766 --> 01:02:55,561
BROOKS: I don't think
the store manager likes me very much.

932
01:02:55,645 --> 01:02:57,437
(Pigeons cooing)

933
01:02:58,523 --> 01:03:03,318
Sometimes, after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

934
01:03:03,403 --> 01:03:08,740
I keep thinking Jake might just show up
and say hello.

935
01:03:08,825 --> 01:03:10,617
But he never does.

936
01:03:11,703 --> 01:03:17,082
And I hope, wherever he is,
he's doing OK and making new friends.

937
01:03:20,587 --> 01:03:23,505
I have trouble sleeping at night.

938
01:03:23,590 --> 01:03:26,383
I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.

939
01:03:27,468 --> 01:03:29,386
I wake up, scared.

940
01:03:29,470 --> 01:03:33,473
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

941
01:03:35,101 --> 01:03:36,560
Maybe I should get me a gun

942
01:03:36,644 --> 01:03:40,522
and rob the Foodway, so they'd send me home.

943
01:03:40,607 --> 01:03:42,941
I could shoot the manager, while I was at it.

944
01:03:43,026 --> 01:03:44,985
Sort of like a bonus.

945
01:03:46,487 --> 01:03:50,741
I guess I'm too old for that sort of nonsense
any more.

946
01:03:50,825 --> 01:03:52,868
I don't like it here.

947
01:03:52,952 --> 01:03:55,621
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.

948
01:03:55,705 --> 01:03:56,788
I've decided...

949
01:03:56,873 --> 01:03:58,749
not to stay.

950
01:04:10,094 --> 01:04:13,597
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.

951
01:04:13,681 --> 01:04:15,766
Not for an old crook like me.

952
01:04:30,615 --> 01:04:32,532
(Scraping)

953
01:05:18,788 --> 01:05:22,833
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.
Not for an old crook like me.

954
01:05:24,001 --> 01:05:28,046
PS. Tell Heywood
I'm sorry I put a knife to his throat.

955
01:05:28,047 --> 01:05:30,132
No hard feelings. Brooks."

956
01:05:40,852 --> 01:05:42,936
He should have died in here.

957
01:05:48,359 --> 01:05:52,821
HADLEY: What the fuck have you done?
It's a goddamn mess. I'll tell you that.

958
01:05:57,535 --> 01:05:58,952
What's all this?

959
01:05:59,036 --> 01:06:02,914
You tell me, fuck-stick.
They're all addressed to you.

960
01:06:02,999 --> 01:06:04,291
Take it.

961
01:06:13,259 --> 01:06:14,843
"Dear Mr. Dufresne...

962
01:06:15,928 --> 01:06:17,929
In response to your repeated enquiries,

963
01:06:18,014 --> 01:06:22,726
the State has allocated the enclosed funds
for your library project."

964
01:06:22,810 --> 01:06:24,186
This is 200 dollars.

965
01:06:25,229 --> 01:06:29,149
"In addition, the Library District
has generously responded

966
01:06:29,233 --> 01:06:31,943
with a charitable donation
of used books and sundries.

967
01:06:32,028 --> 01:06:34,112
We trust this will fill your needs.

968
01:06:34,197 --> 01:06:38,325
We now consider the matter closed.
Please stop sending us letters."

969
01:06:38,409 --> 01:06:41,244
I want all this cleared out
before the Warden gets back.

970
01:06:41,329 --> 01:06:42,996
Yes, sir.

971
01:06:46,751 --> 01:06:48,126
Good for you, Andy.

972
01:06:50,755 --> 01:06:52,214
Wow!

973
01:06:53,299 --> 01:06:55,383
It only took six years.

974
01:06:56,677 --> 01:06:59,554
From now on,
I'll write two letters a week, instead of one.

975
01:06:59,639 --> 01:07:03,183
Oh, I believe you're crazy enough.
You'd better get all this stuff out,

976
01:07:03,267 --> 01:07:04,434
like the Captain said.

977
01:07:04,519 --> 01:07:08,396
Now, I'm gonna go pinch a loaf.
When I come back, this is all gone, right?

978
01:07:14,570 --> 01:07:16,571
Wow.

979
01:07:46,644 --> 01:07:49,354
♪ MOZART:
Duettino from The Marriage Of Figaro

980
01:07:50,815 --> 01:07:53,400
♪ Sull'aria...

981
01:07:57,029 --> 01:07:58,029
Andy,

982
01:07:58,114 --> 01:07:59,447
do you hear that?

983
01:07:59,532 --> 01:08:03,243
♪ ..zeffiretto

984
01:08:11,711 --> 01:08:13,545
(Locks door)

985
01:08:15,464 --> 01:08:23,305
♪ Questa sera spirera

986
01:08:32,023 --> 01:08:33,356
(Feedback hisses)

987
01:08:35,568 --> 01:08:38,486
(Music over loudspeakers)

988
01:08:42,491 --> 01:08:44,576
(Aria continues)

989
01:08:53,711 --> 01:08:58,006
♪ Sotto i pini

990
01:08:58,090 --> 01:09:03,303
♪ Del boschetto

991
01:09:04,805 --> 01:09:07,182
♪ Sotto i pini...

992
01:09:07,266 --> 01:09:10,143
(Banging at door) Dufresne?

993
01:09:10,227 --> 01:09:11,811
Dufresne?

994
01:09:11,896 --> 01:09:13,980
Andy, let me out.

995
01:09:16,692 --> 01:09:20,236
Andy?

996
01:09:20,321 --> 01:09:25,492
RED: I have no idea to this day
what those two Italian ladies were singing about.

997
01:09:25,576 --> 01:09:27,994
The truth is, I don't want to know.

998
01:09:28,079 --> 01:09:30,163
Some things are best left unsaid.

999
01:09:34,210 --> 01:09:39,255
I like to think they were singing about something
so beautiful, it can't be expressed in words...

1000
01:09:39,340 --> 01:09:41,716
and makes your heart ache because of it.

1001
01:09:43,928 --> 01:09:46,638
I tell you, those voices soared...

1002
01:09:46,722 --> 01:09:51,267
higher and farther
than anybody in a grey place dares to dream.

1003
01:09:51,352 --> 01:09:54,729
It was like some beautiful bird
flapped into our drab little cage

1004
01:09:54,814 --> 01:09:57,941
and made those walls dissolve away.

1005
01:09:58,025 --> 01:10:00,360
And for the briefest of moments...

1006
01:10:00,444 --> 01:10:03,530
every last man at Shawshank felt free.

1007
01:10:06,033 --> 01:10:08,535
It pissed the Warden off something awful.

1008
01:10:09,954 --> 01:10:11,079
Open the door.

1009
01:10:13,833 --> 01:10:15,750
Open it up!

1010
01:10:16,961 --> 01:10:19,337
Dufresne, open this door!

1011
01:10:19,422 --> 01:10:20,880
(Bangs door)

1012
01:10:20,965 --> 01:10:22,298
Turn that off!

1013
01:10:22,383 --> 01:10:24,467
(Bangs door)

1014
01:10:26,137 --> 01:10:29,014
(Aria continues)

1015
01:10:29,098 --> 01:10:31,850
I am warning you, Dufresne. Turn that off!

1016
01:10:35,354 --> 01:10:37,439
(Increases volume)

1017
01:10:45,698 --> 01:10:47,574
Dufresne...

1018
01:10:48,701 --> 01:10:50,785
You're mine now.

1019
01:10:58,335 --> 01:11:01,087
RED: Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

1020
01:11:01,172 --> 01:11:03,590
(Hadley stops record) On your feet!

1021
01:11:04,800 --> 01:11:06,885
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

1022
01:11:08,387 --> 01:11:12,432
Y-Y-You couldn't play something good, huh?
Hank Williams or something?

1023
01:11:12,516 --> 01:11:15,185
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

1024
01:11:15,269 --> 01:11:17,062
Was it worth it, two weeks in the hole?

1025
01:11:17,146 --> 01:11:18,396
Easiest time I ever did.

1026
01:11:18,481 --> 01:11:21,524
Bullshit!
There's no such thing as easy time in the hole.

1027
01:11:21,525 --> 01:11:24,152
A week in the hole is like a year.

1028
01:11:24,236 --> 01:11:26,946
I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

1029
01:11:27,031 --> 01:11:30,366
So, they let you tote that record player
down there, huh?

1030
01:11:32,495 --> 01:11:34,120
It was in here.

1031
01:11:34,205 --> 01:11:35,872
And in here.

1032
01:11:37,083 --> 01:11:41,336
That's the beauty of music.
They can't get that from you.

1033
01:11:45,257 --> 01:11:47,759
Haven't you ever felt that way about music?

1034
01:11:49,428 --> 01:11:53,515
Well, I played a mean harmonica,
as a younger man.

1035
01:11:53,599 --> 01:11:55,391
Lost interest in it, though.

1036
01:11:55,476 --> 01:11:57,310
Didn't make much sense in here.

1037
01:11:57,394 --> 01:11:59,854
Here's where it makes the most sense.

1038
01:11:59,939 --> 01:12:02,524
You need it, so you don't forget.

1039
01:12:02,608 --> 01:12:03,942
Forget?

1040
01:12:04,026 --> 01:12:05,985
Forget that...

1041
01:12:06,070 --> 01:12:08,154
there are places...

1042
01:12:09,490 --> 01:12:12,033
..in the world that aren't made out of stone...

1043
01:12:12,118 --> 01:12:14,160
that there's a...

1044
01:12:14,245 --> 01:12:16,079
there's something...

1045
01:12:16,163 --> 01:12:18,957
inside that they can't get to...

1046
01:12:19,041 --> 01:12:21,334
that they can't touch.

1047
01:12:21,418 --> 01:12:23,294
It's yours.

1048
01:12:24,713 --> 01:12:26,422
What are you talking about?

1049
01:12:27,508 --> 01:12:29,092
Hope.

1050
01:12:29,176 --> 01:12:31,052
Hope?

1051
01:12:32,888 --> 01:12:35,557
Let me tell you something, my friend.

1052
01:12:35,641 --> 01:12:37,600
Hope is a dangerous thing.

1053
01:12:39,186 --> 01:12:41,229
Hope can drive a man insane.

1054
01:12:42,273 --> 01:12:44,190
It's got no use on the inside.

1055
01:12:44,275 --> 01:12:46,943
You'd better get used to that idea.

1056
01:12:49,363 --> 01:12:50,989
Like Brooks did?

1057
01:13:16,223 --> 01:13:17,265
Sit down.

1058
01:13:22,479 --> 01:13:25,940
It says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

1059
01:13:26,025 --> 01:13:28,651
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1060
01:13:28,736 --> 01:13:30,820
Oh, yes, sir.

1061
01:13:30,821 --> 01:13:32,906
Without a doubt.

1062
01:13:33,949 --> 01:13:36,284
And I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

1063
01:13:38,871 --> 01:13:40,914
No danger to society here.

1064
01:13:40,998 --> 01:13:43,082
God's honest truth.

1065
01:13:45,419 --> 01:13:47,503
Absolutely rehabilitated.

1066
01:13:57,431 --> 01:13:59,515
30 years.

1067
01:14:00,601 --> 01:14:02,644
Jesus, when they say it like that...

1068
01:14:02,728 --> 01:14:04,812
You wonder where it went.

1069
01:14:07,775 --> 01:14:09,859
I wonder where ten years went.

1070
01:14:14,907 --> 01:14:16,199
Here.

1071
01:14:16,283 --> 01:14:18,451
Little parole rejection present.

1072
01:14:20,287 --> 01:14:22,330
Go ahead and open it.

1073
01:14:22,414 --> 01:14:26,209
I had to go through one of your competitors.
I hope you don't mind.

1074
01:14:26,293 --> 01:14:28,378
I wanted it to be a surprise.

1075
01:14:38,514 --> 01:14:40,598
It's very pretty, Andy.

1076
01:14:41,684 --> 01:14:43,768
Thank you.

1077
01:14:45,521 --> 01:14:47,605
Are you going to play it?

1078
01:14:51,735 --> 01:14:53,820
No.

1079
01:14:56,115 --> 01:14:58,199
Not right now.

1080
01:15:03,330 --> 01:15:05,373
(Guards shout)

1081
01:15:05,457 --> 01:15:07,542
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1082
01:15:08,585 --> 01:15:10,628
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1083
01:15:10,713 --> 01:15:12,797
Tier 1 South. Clear.

1084
01:15:15,634 --> 01:15:17,719
Fall in!

1085
01:15:20,431 --> 01:15:22,515
(Gate buzzer)

1086
01:15:50,169 --> 01:15:52,211
(Guard's footsteps)

1087
01:15:52,296 --> 01:15:53,880
Lights out!

1088
01:15:53,964 --> 01:15:55,465
(Click of light switches)

1089
01:16:00,888 --> 01:16:02,972
(Guard walks away)

1090
01:16:09,146 --> 01:16:11,230
(Outer door closes)

1091
01:16:20,074 --> 01:16:22,158
(Gently plays one note)

1092
01:16:27,581 --> 01:16:28,706
(Hammering)

1093
01:16:28,791 --> 01:16:30,833
RED: Andy was as good as his word.

1094
01:16:30,918 --> 01:16:33,419
He wrote two letters a week instead of one.

1095
01:16:36,048 --> 01:16:40,176
In 1959, the State Senate
finally clued into the fact

1096
01:16:40,260 --> 01:16:43,137
they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.

1097
01:16:43,222 --> 01:16:49,811
Appropriations Committee voted
an annual payment of $500 just to shut him up.

1098
01:16:49,895 --> 01:16:51,604
And you'd be amazed

1099
01:16:51,688 --> 01:16:53,356
how far Andy could stretch it.

1100
01:16:53,440 --> 01:16:56,317
He made deals with book clubs, charity groups.

1101
01:16:56,402 --> 01:16:58,778
He bought remaindered books by the pound.

1102
01:16:58,862 --> 01:17:01,072
Treasure Island.

1103
01:17:01,156 --> 01:17:03,324
Robert Louis...

1104
01:17:03,409 --> 01:17:04,617
..Stevenson.

1105
01:17:04,701 --> 01:17:06,160
Fiction, adventure.

1106
01:17:08,163 --> 01:17:09,789
What's next?

1107
01:17:09,790 --> 01:17:12,500
I got here Auto Repair and...

1108
01:17:13,544 --> 01:17:14,877
..Soap Carving.

1109
01:17:14,962 --> 01:17:18,339
Trade skills and hobbies. Goes under
Educational. The stack behind you.

1110
01:17:18,424 --> 01:17:20,466
The Count Of Monte Crisco.

1111
01:17:20,551 --> 01:17:22,885
That's Cristo, you dumb shit.

1112
01:17:22,970 --> 01:17:26,764
By Alexandree...Dumass.

1113
01:17:26,849 --> 01:17:31,769
Dumb-ass?

1114
01:17:34,273 --> 01:17:36,607
Dumas. You know what that's about?

1115
01:17:36,692 --> 01:17:38,067
Uh-uh.

1116
01:17:38,152 --> 01:17:40,862
You'll like it. It's about a prison break.

1117
01:17:40,946 --> 01:17:44,949
We ought to file that under Educational, too,
oughtn't we?

1118
01:17:45,033 --> 01:17:49,203
RED: The rest of us did our best to pitch in
when and where we could.

1119
01:17:50,456 --> 01:17:52,290
By the year Kennedy was shot,

1120
01:17:52,374 --> 01:17:56,711
Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of rat turds and turpentine

1121
01:17:56,712 --> 01:18:00,047
into the best prison library in New England,

1122
01:18:00,132 --> 01:18:04,010
complete with a fine selection of Hank Williams.

1123
01:18:04,094 --> 01:18:08,264
♪ Lawd I don't know what I'll do-ooo

1124
01:18:08,348 --> 01:18:11,100
♪ All I do is sit and sigh...

1125
01:18:11,185 --> 01:18:15,938
RED: That was also the year Warden Norton
instituted his famous Inside Out program.

1126
01:18:16,023 --> 01:18:18,733
You may remember reading about it.

1127
01:18:18,817 --> 01:18:22,236
It made all the papers
and got his picture in Look Magazine.

1128
01:18:22,321 --> 01:18:23,988
No free ride.

1129
01:18:24,072 --> 01:18:27,033
But rather a genuine, progressive advance

1130
01:18:27,117 --> 01:18:29,285
in corrections and rehabilitation.

1131
01:18:30,329 --> 01:18:32,663
Our inmates, properly supervised,

1132
01:18:32,748 --> 01:18:35,500
will be put to work outside these walls,

1133
01:18:35,584 --> 01:18:37,668
performing all manner of public service.

1134
01:18:37,753 --> 01:18:41,672
These men can learn
the value of an honest day's labor,

1135
01:18:41,757 --> 01:18:45,426
while providing a valuable service
to the community and...

1136
01:18:45,511 --> 01:18:50,723
at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. and Mrs. John Q Taxpayer.

1137
01:18:50,807 --> 01:18:53,476
RED: Of course,
Norton failed to mention to the press

1138
01:18:53,560 --> 01:18:56,854
that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

1139
01:18:56,939 --> 01:19:00,107
There are a hundred different ways
to skim off the top.

1140
01:19:00,192 --> 01:19:02,818
Men, materials, you name it.

1141
01:19:03,862 --> 01:19:06,614
And, oh, my Lord, how the money rolled in.

1142
01:19:06,698 --> 01:19:08,824
If this keeps up, you'll put me out of business.

1143
01:19:08,909 --> 01:19:11,077
- Ned!
- This pool of slave labor you've got,

1144
01:19:11,161 --> 01:19:13,204
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1145
01:19:13,288 --> 01:19:17,250
Ned, we're providing
a valuable community service here.

1146
01:19:17,334 --> 01:19:19,585
Well, that's fine for the papers

1147
01:19:19,670 --> 01:19:21,170
but I've got a family to feed.

1148
01:19:21,255 --> 01:19:22,964
Sam...

1149
01:19:23,048 --> 01:19:25,508
Sam, we go back a long way.

1150
01:19:25,592 --> 01:19:27,927
I need this new highway contract.

1151
01:19:28,011 --> 01:19:30,221
I don't get it, and I go under.

1152
01:19:30,305 --> 01:19:32,348
That's a fact.

1153
01:19:32,432 --> 01:19:34,517
You just have some of this fine pie

1154
01:19:34,601 --> 01:19:36,644
my missus made especially for you,

1155
01:19:36,728 --> 01:19:38,062
and you think about that.

1156
01:19:46,113 --> 01:19:49,031
Ned, I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1157
01:19:49,116 --> 01:19:52,326
It seems to me I already got
my boys committed elsewhere.

1158
01:19:54,204 --> 01:19:56,789
You be sure and thank Maisie for this fine pie.

1159
01:19:58,417 --> 01:20:00,585
RED: And behind every shady deal,

1160
01:20:00,669 --> 01:20:02,878
behind every dollar earned,

1161
01:20:02,963 --> 01:20:06,132
there was Andy, keeping the books.

1162
01:20:07,175 --> 01:20:10,595
Two deposits.
Maine National and New England First.

1163
01:20:10,679 --> 01:20:12,763
Night drops as always, sir.

1164
01:20:43,170 --> 01:20:44,920
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1165
01:20:45,005 --> 01:20:47,798
- Two suits for dry-clean and a bag of whatnot.
- Yes, sir.

1166
01:20:47,883 --> 01:20:51,636
Tell them if they over-starch my shirts again,
they'll hear about it from me.

1167
01:20:51,720 --> 01:20:53,721
How do I look?

1168
01:20:53,805 --> 01:20:56,515
- Very nice, sir.
- Big charity to-do up Portland way.

1169
01:20:56,600 --> 01:20:58,309
The Governor's going to be there.

1170
01:20:59,728 --> 01:21:01,771
Want the rest of this?

1171
01:21:01,855 --> 01:21:03,939
The woman can't bake worth shit.

1172
01:21:05,317 --> 01:21:07,109
Thank you, sir.

1173
01:21:09,279 --> 01:21:13,032
- He's got his fingers in a lot of pies, I hear.
- What you hear isn't half of it.

1174
01:21:13,116 --> 01:21:15,576
He's got scams you haven't even dreamed of.

1175
01:21:15,661 --> 01:21:17,703
Kickbacks on his kickbacks.

1176
01:21:17,788 --> 01:21:20,665
There's a river of dirty money
running through this place.

1177
01:21:20,749 --> 01:21:24,001
But the problem with having all that money
is you'll have to explain

1178
01:21:24,086 --> 01:21:26,671
- where it came from.
- That's where I come in.

1179
01:21:26,755 --> 01:21:29,256
I channel it, filter it, funnel it.

1180
01:21:29,341 --> 01:21:31,884
Stocks, securities, tax-free municipals.

1181
01:21:31,968 --> 01:21:34,637
I send that money out into the real world.

1182
01:21:34,721 --> 01:21:38,349
- And when it comes back...
- Clean as a virgin's honey pot, huh?

1183
01:21:38,433 --> 01:21:39,642
Cleaner.

1184
01:21:39,726 --> 01:21:43,354
By the time Norton retires,
I'll have made him a millionaire.

1185
01:21:46,108 --> 01:21:50,528
If they ever catch on, though, he's gonna
wind up in here wearing a number himself.

1186
01:21:50,612 --> 01:21:53,864
Now, Red, I thought you had
a little more faith in me than that.

1187
01:21:53,949 --> 01:21:57,243
I know you're good, Andy,
but all that paper leaves a trail.

1188
01:21:57,327 --> 01:22:00,329
Now, anybody gets curious,
the FBI, the IRS, whatever,

1189
01:22:00,414 --> 01:22:03,249
it's gonna lead to somebody.

1190
01:22:03,333 --> 01:22:05,292
Sure it is. But not to me.

1191
01:22:05,377 --> 01:22:07,378
And certainly not to the Warden.

1192
01:22:11,425 --> 01:22:12,717
All right. Who?

1193
01:22:12,801 --> 01:22:14,510
Randall Stevens.

1194
01:22:14,594 --> 01:22:15,761
Who?

1195
01:22:16,847 --> 01:22:21,559
The silent silent partner. He's the guilty one,
Your Honor. The man with the bank accounts.

1196
01:22:21,643 --> 01:22:23,811
That's where the filtering process starts.

1197
01:22:23,895 --> 01:22:27,064
If they trace anything,
it's just going to lead to him.

1198
01:22:27,149 --> 01:22:28,733
But who is he?

1199
01:22:28,817 --> 01:22:30,860
He's a phantom, an apparition.

1200
01:22:30,944 --> 01:22:32,903
Second cousin to Harvey the Rabbit.

1201
01:22:32,988 --> 01:22:35,156
I conjured him...

1202
01:22:35,240 --> 01:22:37,283
out of thin air.

1203
01:22:37,367 --> 01:22:40,202
He doesn't exist, except on paper.

1204
01:22:43,331 --> 01:22:45,708
Andy, you can’t just make a person up.

1205
01:22:45,792 --> 01:22:48,919
Sure you can, if you know how
the system works, where the cracks are.

1206
01:22:49,004 --> 01:22:52,506
It's amazing what you can accomplish by mail.

1207
01:22:52,591 --> 01:22:55,217
Mr. Stevens has a birth certificate,

1208
01:22:55,302 --> 01:22:57,636
a driver's license, social security number.

1209
01:22:57,721 --> 01:22:58,929
You're shitting me?

1210
01:22:59,014 --> 01:23:00,973
If they ever trace any of those accounts,

1211
01:23:01,057 --> 01:23:03,934
they're going to wind up chasing
a figment of my imagination.

1212
01:23:04,019 --> 01:23:06,103
Well, I'll be damned.

1213
01:23:07,397 --> 01:23:09,440
Did I say you were good?

1214
01:23:09,524 --> 01:23:11,692
Shit, you're a Rembrandt!

1215
01:23:11,777 --> 01:23:13,819
You know, the funny thing is,

1216
01:23:13,904 --> 01:23:17,865
on the outside, I was an honest man,
straight as an arrow.

1217
01:23:18,909 --> 01:23:21,285
I had to come to prison to be a crook.

1218
01:23:30,045 --> 01:23:31,420
Ever bother you?

1219
01:23:32,464 --> 01:23:35,883
I don't run the scams, Red,
I just process the profits.

1220
01:23:35,967 --> 01:23:38,010
Fine line maybe but...

1221
01:23:38,094 --> 01:23:40,805
I also built that library

1222
01:23:40,889 --> 01:23:43,516
and used it to help a dozen guys
get a high school diploma.

1223
01:23:43,600 --> 01:23:45,476
Why do you think the Warden lets me do it?

1224
01:23:45,560 --> 01:23:48,312
To keep you happy and doing the laundry.

1225
01:23:48,396 --> 01:23:50,523
Money instead of sheets.

1226
01:23:50,607 --> 01:23:53,317
Well, I work cheap. That's the trade-off.

1227
01:23:53,401 --> 01:23:55,486
(Siren wails)

1228
01:23:58,907 --> 01:24:01,116
♪ JOHNNY OTIS: Willy And The Hand Jive

1229
01:24:08,917 --> 01:24:10,709
♪ I know a cat named...

1230
01:24:10,794 --> 01:24:13,462
RED: Tommy Williams
came to Shawshank in 1965

1231
01:24:13,547 --> 01:24:15,589
on a two-year stretch for B&E.

1232
01:24:15,674 --> 01:24:17,800
That's breaking and entering to you.

1233
01:24:17,884 --> 01:24:22,513
The cops caught him sneaking TV sets
out the back door of a JC Penney.

1234
01:24:22,597 --> 01:24:24,348
Young punk.

1235
01:24:24,432 --> 01:24:26,475
Mr. Rock'n'roll.

1236
01:24:26,560 --> 01:24:28,227
Cocky as hell.

1237
01:24:28,311 --> 01:24:30,896
Hey, come on, old boys! Moving like molasses!

1238
01:24:30,981 --> 01:24:32,940
Making me look bad.

1239
01:24:32,941 --> 01:24:34,900
RED: We liked him immediately.

1240
01:24:34,985 --> 01:24:37,027
So I'm backing out the door, right?

1241
01:24:37,112 --> 01:24:38,821
And I got the TV like this.

1242
01:24:38,905 --> 01:24:42,741
It was a big old thing. I couldn't see shit.
Suddenly, I hears this voice.

1243
01:24:42,826 --> 01:24:44,869
"Freeze, kid! Hands in the air."

1244
01:24:44,953 --> 01:24:46,620
Well, I just stand there,

1245
01:24:46,705 --> 01:24:49,498
holding onto that TV. So, finally, the voice says,

1246
01:24:49,583 --> 01:24:51,542
"Do you hear what I said, boy?"

1247
01:24:51,626 --> 01:24:54,003
I say, "Yes, sir, I sure did.

1248
01:24:54,087 --> 01:24:57,715
But if I drop this fucking thing,
you got me on destruction of property, too."

1249
01:24:57,799 --> 01:24:59,925
(Laughter)

1250
01:25:01,803 --> 01:25:04,513
Hey, you've done a stretch in Cashman, right?

1251
01:25:04,598 --> 01:25:08,434
Yeah. Yeah, that was an easy piece of time,
let me tell you.

1252
01:25:08,518 --> 01:25:11,145
Weekend furloughs, work programs.

1253
01:25:11,229 --> 01:25:12,646
Not like here.

1254
01:25:12,731 --> 01:25:15,065
Sounds like you done time
all over New England.

1255
01:25:15,150 --> 01:25:20,237
Yeah, I've been in and out since I was 13. You
name the place, chances are I've been there.

1256
01:25:20,322 --> 01:25:24,325
Perhaps it's time you tried a new profession?

1257
01:25:24,409 --> 01:25:29,496
What I mean is, you don't seem to be a good
thief. Maybe you should try something else.

1258
01:25:29,581 --> 01:25:33,417
Yeah, well, what the hell
do you know about it, Capone?

1259
01:25:33,501 --> 01:25:35,252
