01:42:44,239 --> 01:42:47,992
I just didn't expect
the storm would last as long as it has.

1514
01:42:52,081 --> 01:42:53,998
Do you think you'll ever get out of here?

1515
01:42:55,250 --> 01:42:56,918
Me?

1516
01:42:59,213 --> 01:43:00,672
Yeah.

1517
01:43:01,715 --> 01:43:03,675
One day, when I've got a long, white beard

1518
01:43:03,759 --> 01:43:07,261
and two or three marbles rolling around upstairs,
they'll let me out.

1519
01:43:09,181 --> 01:43:11,265
I tell you where I'd go.

1520
01:43:12,476 --> 01:43:14,102
Zihuatanejo.

1521
01:43:14,186 --> 01:43:16,104
Zi...what?

1522
01:43:16,188 --> 01:43:18,231
Zihuatanejo.

1523
01:43:18,315 --> 01:43:20,400
It's in Mexico.

1524
01:43:22,194 --> 01:43:24,404
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1525
01:43:25,656 --> 01:43:28,032
You know what the Mexicans say
about the Pacific?

1526
01:43:28,117 --> 01:43:29,575
No.

1527
01:43:29,660 --> 01:43:31,744
They say it has no memory.

1528
01:43:34,206 --> 01:43:36,749
That's where I want to live the rest of my life.

1529
01:43:38,335 --> 01:43:40,420
A warm place with no memory.

1530
01:43:43,716 --> 01:43:46,009
Open up a little hotel,

1531
01:43:47,845 --> 01:43:49,721
right on the beach.

1532
01:43:49,805 --> 01:43:51,848
Buy some worthless old boat,

1533
01:43:51,932 --> 01:43:54,017
fix it up new.

1534
01:43:56,979 --> 01:43:58,187
Take my guests out.

1535
01:43:58,272 --> 01:44:00,356
Charter fishing.

1536
01:44:04,278 --> 01:44:06,904
Zihuatanejo, huh?

1537
01:44:09,533 --> 01:44:13,411
In a place like that, I could use a man
who knows how to get things.

1538
01:44:19,835 --> 01:44:22,545
I don't think I could make it on the outside, Andy.

1539
01:44:29,303 --> 01:44:31,387
I've been in here most of my life.

1540
01:44:32,890 --> 01:44:34,682
I'm an institutional man now.

1541
01:44:34,767 --> 01:44:36,851
Just like Brooks was.

1542
01:44:38,270 --> 01:44:40,521
Well, you underestimate yourself.

1543
01:44:40,606 --> 01:44:42,690
I don't think so.

1544
01:44:45,319 --> 01:44:49,530
I mean...in here, I'm the guy
who can get things for you, sure.

1545
01:44:49,615 --> 01:44:53,534
But outside, all you need is the Yellow Pages.

1546
01:44:53,619 --> 01:44:56,037
Hell, I wouldn't even know where to begin.

1547
01:44:58,123 --> 01:45:00,458
The Pacific Ocean?

1548
01:45:00,542 --> 01:45:02,585
Shit.

1549
01:45:02,669 --> 01:45:05,838
- About scare me to death, something that big.
- Not me.

1550
01:45:05,923 --> 01:45:09,383
I didn't shoot my wife and I didn't shoot her lover.

1551
01:45:11,303 --> 01:45:14,931
Whatever mistakes I've made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1552
01:45:15,015 --> 01:45:17,183
That hotel, that boat.

1553
01:45:18,769 --> 01:45:20,937
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1554
01:45:25,567 --> 01:45:28,444
I don't think you ought to be
doing this to yourself, Andy.

1555
01:45:28,529 --> 01:45:30,571
These are just shitty pipe dreams.

1556
01:45:30,656 --> 01:45:33,616
I mean, Mexico is way the hell down there
and you're in here.

1557
01:45:33,700 --> 01:45:35,743
And that's the way it is.

1558
01:45:35,828 --> 01:45:38,454
Yeah, right. That's the way it is.

1559
01:45:40,207 --> 01:45:42,291
It's down there and I'm in here.

1560
01:45:45,003 --> 01:45:47,797
I guess it comes down to a simple choice, really.

1561
01:45:50,634 --> 01:45:52,677
Get busy living

1562
01:45:52,761 --> 01:45:55,680
or get busy dying.

1563
01:45:59,476 --> 01:46:01,561
Andy.

1564
01:46:04,022 --> 01:46:06,107
Red.

1565
01:46:07,151 --> 01:46:09,569
If you ever get out of here, do me a favor.

1566
01:46:09,653 --> 01:46:11,487
Sure, Andy.

1567
01:46:11,572 --> 01:46:12,905
Anything.

1568
01:46:13,991 --> 01:46:17,451
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1569
01:46:19,454 --> 01:46:23,249
- Well, just... There's a lot of hayfields up there.
- One in particular.

1570
01:46:23,333 --> 01:46:25,376
It's got a long rock wall

1571
01:46:25,460 --> 01:46:27,378
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1572
01:46:27,462 --> 01:46:30,173
It's like something out of a Robert Frost poem.

1573
01:46:31,550 --> 01:46:34,260
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1574
01:46:35,470 --> 01:46:39,265
We went there for a picnic
and made love under that oak.

1575
01:46:40,767 --> 01:46:42,852
I asked and she said yes.

1576
01:46:46,982 --> 01:46:49,025
Promise me, Red,

1577
01:46:49,109 --> 01:46:51,110
if you ever get out,

1578
01:46:51,195 --> 01:46:53,237
find that spot.

1579
01:46:54,281 --> 01:46:59,744
At the base of that wall, you'll find a rock that has
no earthly business in a Maine hayfield.

1580
01:46:59,828 --> 01:47:02,330
A piece of black, volcanic glass.

1581
01:47:05,500 --> 01:47:08,294
There's something buried under it
I want you to have.

1582
01:47:08,378 --> 01:47:10,379
What, Andy?

1583
01:47:10,464 --> 01:47:12,548
What's buried under there?

1584
01:47:14,343 --> 01:47:17,720
You'll have to pry it up to see.

1585
01:47:23,060 --> 01:47:25,144
No, I'm telling you, the guy is...

1586
01:47:26,188 --> 01:47:28,272
He's talking funnier.

1587
01:47:28,357 --> 01:47:31,734
- I'm really worried about him.
- We ought to keep an eye on him.

1588
01:47:31,818 --> 01:47:35,863
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's got that cell all to himself.

1589
01:47:36,949 --> 01:47:38,407
Oh, Lord.

1590
01:47:38,492 --> 01:47:40,534
What?

1591
01:47:42,204 --> 01:47:44,538
Andy come down to the loading dock today.

1592
01:47:44,623 --> 01:47:48,125
- He asked me for a length of rope.
- Rope?

1593
01:47:48,210 --> 01:47:50,044
Six feet long.

1594
01:47:50,128 --> 01:47:51,587
And you gave it to him?

1595
01:47:51,672 --> 01:47:54,340
Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?

1596
01:47:54,341 --> 01:47:56,050
Jesus, Heywood.

1597
01:47:56,134 --> 01:47:58,386
Hey, how the hell was I supposed to know?

1598
01:47:58,470 --> 01:48:00,388
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1599
01:48:00,472 --> 01:48:01,514
No.

1600
01:48:02,557 --> 01:48:04,767
Andy would never do that.

1601
01:48:04,768 --> 01:48:06,852
Never.

1602
01:48:07,896 --> 01:48:09,981
I don't know.

1603
01:48:12,025 --> 01:48:14,110
Every man has his breaking point.

1604
01:48:16,738 --> 01:48:17,989
Lickety-split.

1605
01:48:18,073 --> 01:48:20,950
- I want to get home.
- Just about finished, sir.

1606
01:48:37,050 --> 01:48:39,135
Three deposits tonight.

1607
01:48:47,519 --> 01:48:49,603
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1608
01:48:49,604 --> 01:48:53,065
And shine my shoes.
I want 'em looking like mirrors.

1609
01:48:53,150 --> 01:48:54,525
Yes, sir.

1610
01:48:59,823 --> 01:49:01,490
It's good having you back, Andy.

1611
01:49:01,575 --> 01:49:04,327
The place wasn't the same without you.

1612
01:49:06,455 --> 01:49:08,539
(Whistles)

1613
01:49:51,375 --> 01:49:54,126
GUARD: Lights out!
(Click of light switches)

1614
01:49:58,423 --> 01:50:00,508
(Footsteps)

1615
01:50:06,390 --> 01:50:08,474
(Outer door closes)

1616
01:50:24,866 --> 01:50:27,159
RED: I've had some long nights in stir.

1617
01:50:28,203 --> 01:50:30,913
Alone in the dark with nothing but your thoughts,

1618
01:50:30,997 --> 01:50:32,832
time can draw out like a blade.

1619
01:50:32,833 --> 01:50:34,917
(Thunder rumbles)

1620
01:50:39,214 --> 01:50:41,549
That was the longest night of my life.

1621
01:50:51,768 --> 01:50:54,103
(Gate buzzer)

1622
01:50:57,691 --> 01:50:59,316
GUARD: Give me a count.

1623
01:51:03,655 --> 01:51:05,698
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1624
01:51:05,782 --> 01:51:07,116
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1625
01:51:07,200 --> 01:51:10,786
- Tier 3 North. Clear.
- Man missing on Tier 2.

1626
01:51:10,871 --> 01:51:13,956
- Cell 245.
- Dufresne.

1627
01:51:14,040 --> 01:51:16,959
Get your ass out here, boy.
You're holding up the show.

1628
01:51:19,463 --> 01:51:23,507
Don't make me come down there.
I'll thump your skull for you.

1629
01:51:31,099 --> 01:51:34,477
Damn it, Dufresne, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1630
01:51:34,561 --> 01:51:37,646
You'd better be sick or dead in there,
I shit you not!

1631
01:51:37,731 --> 01:51:39,565
You hear me?

1632
01:51:46,072 --> 01:51:48,157
Oh, my holy God.

1633
01:52:00,253 --> 01:52:02,338
(Siren wails)

1634
01:52:05,008 --> 01:52:07,718
I want every man on this cell block questioned.

1635
01:52:07,719 --> 01:52:09,929
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1636
01:52:10,013 --> 01:52:11,222
Him!

1637
01:52:13,141 --> 01:52:15,226
Open 237.

1638
01:52:18,230 --> 01:52:20,356
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1639
01:52:20,440 --> 01:52:21,982
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1640
01:52:22,067 --> 01:52:24,318
Don't say that to me again.

1641
01:52:24,402 --> 01:52:25,486
But, sir, he wasn't.

1642
01:52:25,570 --> 01:52:27,738
I can see that, Haig!

1643
01:52:27,822 --> 01:52:29,615
You think I'm blind?

1644
01:52:29,616 --> 01:52:32,743
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1645
01:52:32,827 --> 01:52:33,827
No, sir.

1646
01:52:33,912 --> 01:52:35,955
What about you?

1647
01:52:36,039 --> 01:52:37,873
Are you blind?

1648
01:52:37,958 --> 01:52:40,501
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1649
01:52:40,585 --> 01:52:43,879
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. See? Right there.

1650
01:52:43,964 --> 01:52:45,839
Dufresne.

1651
01:52:47,092 --> 01:52:48,759
He was in his cell at lights out.

1652
01:52:48,843 --> 01:52:52,054
It stands to reason
he'd still be here in the morning.

1653
01:52:53,139 --> 01:52:55,015
I want him found.

1654
01:52:55,100 --> 01:52:57,685
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast.

1655
01:52:57,769 --> 01:52:58,811
Now!

1656
01:52:58,812 --> 01:53:00,312
Yes, sir!

1657
01:53:01,439 --> 01:53:04,024
Let's go, let's go!
Move your butts! Move it!

1658
01:53:06,861 --> 01:53:07,903
Stand.

1659
01:53:09,030 --> 01:53:10,281
Well?

1660
01:53:13,660 --> 01:53:14,785
Well, what?

1661
01:53:14,869 --> 01:53:18,330
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1662
01:53:19,374 --> 01:53:21,000
He must have said something.

1663
01:53:21,084 --> 01:53:23,127
No, sir, Warden.

1664
01:53:23,211 --> 01:53:24,670
Not a word.

1665
01:53:26,673 --> 01:53:28,674
Lord, it's a miracle!

1666
01:53:29,718 --> 01:53:32,177
A man up and vanished like a fart in the wind.

1667
01:53:32,262 --> 01:53:34,013
Nothing left but...

1668
01:53:34,097 --> 01:53:37,016
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1669
01:53:37,100 --> 01:53:38,851
And that cupcake on the wall.

1670
01:53:38,935 --> 01:53:40,561
Let's ask her.

1671
01:53:40,645 --> 01:53:44,607
Maybe she knows. What say there,
Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1672
01:53:45,692 --> 01:53:46,775
Ah...

1673
01:53:46,776 --> 01:53:48,235
I guess not.

1674
01:53:48,320 --> 01:53:51,196
Why should she be any different?

1675
01:53:51,281 --> 01:53:53,741
This is a conspiracy.

1676
01:53:53,825 --> 01:53:56,035
That's what this is.

1677
01:53:56,119 --> 01:53:57,661
One big...

1678
01:53:57,746 --> 01:54:00,497
damn conspiracy!

1679
01:54:00,582 --> 01:54:03,250
And everyone's in on it!

1680
01:54:03,335 --> 01:54:04,627
Including her!

1681
01:54:05,962 --> 01:54:07,630
(Clattering)

1682
01:54:31,404 --> 01:54:33,113
(Sirens blare)

1683
01:54:39,287 --> 01:54:41,163
RED: In 1966,

1684
01:54:41,247 --> 01:54:43,916
Andy Dufresne escaped

1685
01:54:44,000 --> 01:54:46,085
from Shawshank Prison.

1686
01:54:47,754 --> 01:54:50,506
All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes,

1687
01:54:50,590 --> 01:54:52,633
a bar of soap

1688
01:54:52,717 --> 01:54:57,096
and an old rock hammer
damn near worn down to the nub.

1689
01:55:01,476 --> 01:55:06,313
I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1690
01:55:06,398 --> 01:55:09,108
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1691
01:55:27,669 --> 01:55:29,753
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1692
01:55:30,797 --> 01:55:34,299
I imagine it appealed to his meticulous nature.

1693
01:55:34,384 --> 01:55:36,677
An Ice Age here,

1694
01:55:36,761 --> 01:55:39,346
a million years of mountain-building there.

1695
01:55:40,390 --> 01:55:42,808
Geology is the study of pressure and time.

1696
01:55:44,018 --> 01:55:46,061
That's all it takes, really.

1697
01:55:46,146 --> 01:55:48,188
Pressure...

1698
01:55:48,273 --> 01:55:50,149
and time.

1699
01:55:50,233 --> 01:55:53,569
That and a big goddamn poster.

1700
01:55:54,654 --> 01:55:56,697
(Coughing)

1701
01:55:56,781 --> 01:55:58,157
Like I said,

1702
01:55:58,158 --> 01:56:01,952
in prison, a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1703
01:56:04,748 --> 01:56:09,918
It turns out Andy's favorite hobby
was toting his wall out into the exercise yard.

1704
01:56:10,003 --> 01:56:12,087
A handful at a time.

1705
01:56:13,923 --> 01:56:16,091
I guess after Tommy was killed,

1706
01:56:16,176 --> 01:56:19,011
Andy decided he'd been here
just about long enough.

1707
01:56:19,095 --> 01:56:21,305
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1708
01:56:22,599 --> 01:56:24,683
I'm just about finished, sir.

1709
01:56:46,080 --> 01:56:48,165
Three deposits tonight.

1710
01:56:55,340 --> 01:56:57,382
Andy did like he was told.

1711
01:56:58,426 --> 01:57:01,929
Buffed those shoes to a high mirror shine.

1712
01:57:05,517 --> 01:57:07,559
The guard simply didn't notice.

1713
01:57:07,644 --> 01:57:09,686
Neither did I.

1714
01:57:09,771 --> 01:57:14,107
I mean, seriously, how often
do you really look at a man's shoes?

1715
01:57:48,810 --> 01:57:50,894
(Thunderclap)

1716
01:59:18,149 --> 01:59:24,321
Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards
of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.

1717
01:59:24,405 --> 01:59:25,572
(Gags)

1718
01:59:25,657 --> 01:59:27,658
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1719
01:59:27,742 --> 01:59:29,826
(Coughs and spits)

1720
01:59:32,372 --> 01:59:34,581
500 yards.

1721
01:59:35,625 --> 01:59:38,126
That's the length of five football fields.

1722
01:59:39,170 --> 01:59:41,421
Just shy of half a mile.

1723
02:00:22,964 --> 02:00:24,673
(Laughs)

1724
02:00:36,644 --> 02:00:41,189
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret,

1725
02:00:41,274 --> 02:00:44,693
a man nobody ever laid eyes on before

1726
02:00:44,777 --> 02:00:47,195
strode into the Maine National Bank.

1727
02:00:47,280 --> 02:00:49,322
Until that moment,

1728
02:00:49,407 --> 02:00:51,283
he didn't exist,

1729
02:00:51,367 --> 02:00:52,701
except on paper.

1730
02:00:52,785 --> 02:00:53,827
May I help you?

1731
02:00:53,911 --> 02:00:55,954
RED: He had all the proper ID,

1732
02:00:56,039 --> 02:00:59,666
driver's license, birth certificate,
social security card.

1733
02:00:59,751 --> 02:01:03,045
And the signature was a spot-on match.

1734
02:01:03,129 --> 02:01:06,173
I must say, I'm sorry to be losing your business.

1735
02:01:06,257 --> 02:01:08,258
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1736
02:01:08,342 --> 02:01:10,135
Thank you.

1737
02:01:10,219 --> 02:01:12,012
I'm sure I will.

1738
02:01:12,096 --> 02:01:14,222
Here's your cashier's check, sir.

1739
02:01:14,307 --> 02:01:16,349
Will there be anything else?

1740
02:01:16,434 --> 02:01:17,434
Please...

1741
02:01:17,518 --> 02:01:20,604
Would you add this to your outgoing mail?

1742
02:01:20,688 --> 02:01:22,898
I'd be happy to.

1743
02:01:22,982 --> 02:01:25,317
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

1744
02:01:25,401 --> 02:01:30,197
RED: Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.

1745
02:01:31,365 --> 02:01:37,829
All told, he blew town with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1746
02:01:37,914 --> 02:01:40,373
Severance pay for 19 years.

1747
02:01:40,458 --> 02:01:42,542
(Phone rings)

1748
02:01:48,508 --> 02:01:50,801
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1749
02:01:58,476 --> 02:02:00,560
(Sirens wail)

1750
02:02:29,757 --> 02:02:31,800
(Sirens approaching)

1751
02:02:43,521 --> 02:02:46,523
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1752
02:02:46,607 --> 02:02:51,236
If you give up the right to remain silent, anything
you say will be held against you in court.

1753
02:02:51,320 --> 02:02:53,196
RED: I wasn't there to see it.

1754
02:02:53,281 --> 02:02:58,160
But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing
like a little girl when they took him away.

1755
02:03:03,583 --> 02:03:06,376
Norton had no intention of going that quietly.

1756
02:03:22,351 --> 02:03:23,810
Samuel Norton?

1757
02:03:23,895 --> 02:03:27,147
- We have a warrant for your arrest. Open up.
(Banging on door)

1758
02:03:30,026 --> 02:03:31,151
Norton!

1759
02:03:31,235 --> 02:03:32,903
Open the door.

1760
02:03:32,987 --> 02:03:34,738
I'm not sure which key it is.

1761
02:03:37,617 --> 02:03:39,284
Norton!

1762
02:03:44,749 --> 02:03:46,833
Make it easy on yourself, Norton.

1763
02:03:58,137 --> 02:04:01,723
RED: I like to think
the last thing that went through his head,

1764
02:04:01,807 --> 02:04:03,516
other than that bullet,

1765
02:04:03,601 --> 02:04:07,604
was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1766
02:04:09,273 --> 02:04:10,357
Carter, James...

1767
02:04:10,441 --> 02:04:13,818
RED: Not long after the Warden
deprived us of his company,

1768
02:04:13,903 --> 02:04:16,154
I got a postcard in the mail.

1769
02:04:17,865 --> 02:04:20,283
It was blank but the postmark said...

1770
02:04:20,368 --> 02:04:23,119
Fort Hancock, Texas.

1771
02:04:23,204 --> 02:04:25,247
Fort Hancock.

1772
02:04:25,331 --> 02:04:27,374
Right on the border.

1773
02:04:27,458 --> 02:04:29,501
That's where Andy crossed.

1774
02:04:29,585 --> 02:04:33,463
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down,

1775
02:04:34,507 --> 02:04:36,591
it always makes me laugh.

1776
02:04:38,010 --> 02:04:40,053
Andy Dufresne,

1777
02:04:40,137 --> 02:04:42,514
who crawled through a river of shit

1778
02:04:42,598 --> 02:04:44,683
and came out clean on the other side.

1779
02:04:45,893 --> 02:04:47,936
Andy Dufresne,

1780
02:04:48,020 --> 02:04:49,938
headed for the Pacific.

1781
02:04:52,525 --> 02:04:54,567
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1782
02:04:54,652 --> 02:04:58,863
And he says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1783
02:04:58,948 --> 02:05:02,117
RED: Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1784
02:05:02,201 --> 02:05:04,452
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1785
02:05:04,537 --> 02:05:07,038
"These friends of mine
could use a couple of beers!"

1786
02:05:07,123 --> 02:05:09,207
- And he got it.
- And he got it!

1787
02:05:10,376 --> 02:05:12,752
RED: Sometimes it makes me sad, though,

1788
02:05:12,837 --> 02:05:14,879
Andy being gone.

1789
02:05:14,964 --> 02:05:18,967
I have to remind myself
that some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1790
02:05:20,052 --> 02:05:22,137
Their feathers are just too bright.

1791
02:05:23,681 --> 02:05:25,724
And when they fly away,

1792
02:05:25,808 --> 02:05:29,728
the part of you that knows
it was a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1793
02:05:31,480 --> 02:05:32,939
But still...

1794
02:05:33,024 --> 02:05:37,193
the place you live in is that much more drab
and empty that they're gone.

1795
02:05:41,741 --> 02:05:43,992
I guess I just miss my friend.

1796
02:06:07,975 --> 02:06:09,851
Please sit down.

1797
02:06:15,441 --> 02:06:17,567
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1798
02:06:17,651 --> 02:06:21,029
Your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1799
02:06:21,113 --> 02:06:23,490
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1800
02:06:25,618 --> 02:06:27,702
Rehabilitated?

1801
02:06:29,246 --> 02:06:31,331
Well, now, let me see.

1802
02:06:32,375 --> 02:06:34,709
You know, I don't have any idea
what that means.

1803
02:06:36,504 --> 02:06:39,047
Well, it means you're ready to rejoin society...

1804
02:06:39,131 --> 02:06:41,674
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1805
02:06:44,053 --> 02:06:46,137
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1806
02:06:47,181 --> 02:06:49,432
A politician's word so that...

1807
02:06:49,517 --> 02:06:55,021
young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie and have a job.

1808
02:06:57,441 --> 02:06:59,526
What do you really want to know?

1809
02:07:00,694 --> 02:07:02,612
Am I sorry for what I did?

1810
02:07:02,696 --> 02:07:04,406
Well, are you?

1811
02:07:06,033 --> 02:07:08,618
There's not a day goes by I don't feel regret.

1812
02:07:10,204 --> 02:07:13,331
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1813
02:07:17,128 --> 02:07:19,212
I look back on the way I was then.

1814
02:07:21,799 --> 02:07:23,842
A young...

1815
02:07:23,926 --> 02:07:27,011
stupid kid who committed that terrible crime.

1816
02:07:30,850 --> 02:07:32,934
I wanna talk to him.

1817
02:07:34,311 --> 02:07:36,479
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1818
02:07:37,523 --> 02:07:39,607
tell him the way things are.

1819
02:07:41,777 --> 02:07:43,862
But I can't.

1820
02:07:45,072 --> 02:07:47,157
That kid's long gone.

1821
02:07:48,451 --> 02:07:50,535
This old man is all that's left.

1822
02:07:52,663 --> 02:07:54,164
I gotta live with that.

1823
02:07:55,499 --> 02:07:57,292
Rehabilitated?

1824
02:07:57,376 --> 02:07:59,377
It's just a bullshit word.

1825
02:07:59,462 --> 02:08:05,383
So you go on and stamp your form, sonny,
and stop wasting my time.

1826
02:08:06,469 --> 02:08:08,511
Because to tell you the truth,

1827
02:08:08,596 --> 02:08:11,097
I don't give a shit.

1828
02:08:49,220 --> 02:08:51,304
(Gate closes)

1829
02:09:10,699 --> 02:09:12,784
(Siren passes outside)

1830
02:09:37,309 --> 02:09:39,394
Here you go, miss.

1831
02:09:41,397 --> 02:09:42,855
Rest room break, boss?

1832
02:09:48,904 --> 02:09:53,199
You don't need to ask me every time you need
to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1833
02:09:54,410 --> 02:09:56,077
Yes, sir.

1834
02:10:06,130 --> 02:10:09,173
RED: 40 years
I've been asking permission to piss.

1835
02:10:10,175 --> 02:10:12,385
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1836
02:10:16,515 --> 02:10:18,600
There's a harsh truth to face.

1837
02:10:20,561 --> 02:10:22,895
No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.

1838
02:10:31,113 --> 02:10:34,574
All I do any more
is think of ways to break my parole...

1839
02:10:35,618 --> 02:10:37,702
..so maybe they'd send me back.

1840
02:10:43,208 --> 02:10:45,293
A terrible thing to live in fear.

1841
02:10:46,670 --> 02:10:50,048
Brooks Hatlen knew it, knew it all too well.

1842
02:10:52,217 --> 02:10:55,011
All I want is to be back
where things make sense,

1843
02:10:56,055 --> 02:10:58,556
where I won't have to be afraid all the time.

1844
02:11:01,435 --> 02:11:03,519
Only one thing stops me.

1845
02:11:04,563 --> 02:11:06,648
A promise I made to Andy.

1846
02:11:27,378 --> 02:11:29,462
Here it is.

1847
02:11:39,264 --> 02:11:41,349
Much obliged, sir.

1848
02:15:04,595 --> 02:15:06,679
(Bird calls)

1849
02:15:20,152 --> 02:15:21,444
ANDY: Dear Red,

1850
02:15:21,528 --> 02:15:23,988
if you're reading this, you've gotten out.

1851
02:15:24,072 --> 02:15:28,326
And if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a little further.

1852
02:15:28,410 --> 02:15:30,995
You remember the name of the town, don't you?

1853
02:15:33,290 --> 02:15:35,374
Zihuatanejo.

1854
02:15:36,418 --> 02:15:37,627
I could use a good man

1855
02:15:37,711 --> 02:15:39,754
to help me get my project on wheels.

1856
02:15:39,838 --> 02:15:41,964
I'll keep an eye out for you

1857
02:15:42,049 --> 02:15:44,091
and the chessboard ready.

1858
02:15:45,135 --> 02:15:46,510
Remember, Red,

1859
02:15:46,595 --> 02:15:48,638
hope is a good thing.

1860
02:15:48,722 --> 02:15:50,765
Maybe the best of things.

1861
02:15:50,849 --> 02:15:52,934
And no good thing ever dies.

1862
02:15:53,977 --> 02:15:56,437
I will be hoping that this letter finds you

1863
02:15:56,521 --> 02:15:58,564
and finds you well.

1864
02:15:58,649 --> 02:16:01,150
Your friend, Andy.

1865
02:16:35,727 --> 02:16:39,605
RED: Get busy living or get busy dying.

1866
02:16:42,109 --> 02:16:44,193
That's goddamn right.

1867
02:16:49,700 --> 02:16:51,826
For the second time in my life,

1868
02:16:51,910 --> 02:16:53,995
I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1869
02:16:55,664 --> 02:16:57,748
Parole violation.

1870
02:16:57,749 --> 02:17:01,460
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1871
02:17:02,713 --> 02:17:04,755
Not for an old crook like me.

1872
02:17:04,840 --> 02:17:06,924
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1873
02:17:10,637 --> 02:17:14,765
I find I'm so excited I can barely sit still
or hold a thought in my head.

1874
02:17:15,809 --> 02:17:18,811
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1875
02:17:18,895 --> 02:17:21,605
A free man at the start of a long journey

1876
02:17:21,690 --> 02:17:24,608
whose conclusion is uncertain.

1877
02:17:27,487 --> 02:17:29,655
I hope I can make it across the border.

1878
02:17:31,533 --> 02:17:34,326
I hope to see my friend and shake his hand.

1879
02:17:36,705 --> 02:17:39,915
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1880
02:17:42,669 --> 02:17:44,545
I hope.


